text:
185-191 Washington Street, east side, between Nassau and Concord Streets, showing 189 (next to the 1-story building), the A.A. Low home, birthplace of Seth Low. The building following it (187) was the Howard residence; in which Henry Ward Beecher stayed when he first began preaching in Brooklyn. It was demolished in 1928.

1923.

Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

47-51 Nassau Street, north side, east of Washington Street. Also seen is 171-179 Washington Street, east side, north from Nassau Street. In 1908 the 4th Precinct Police Station was housed in the corner building. The building still stands (1936), but is now used for apartments. In 1929 the frame dwelling at No. 47 Nassau Street, was still occupied.

May 1925.

Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.
